        <ComparisonTable columns={sourceCols} rows={sourceRows} verdict="A licensed breeder and a documented rescue sit at the safe end; an anonymous online marketplace sits at the dangerous end. Everything in between comes down to how much you can verify before you pay." />

        <h3 class={h3}>1. Licensed Breeder — the Lowest-Risk Source</h3>
        <p class={p}>A reputable, USDA-licensed breeder is the safest place to buy an African Grey, full stop. You get a bird raised by someone who is legally accountable, whose birds you can see on live video, and whose paperwork — CITES, DNA, avian-vet certificate — you can verify before a cent changes hands. It isn't the cheapest headline price, but it's the only source where the price, the papers and the support all line up.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>What "licensed" actually means (USDA AWA)</h4>
        <p class={p}>"Licensed" isn't a marketing word. A breeder selling regulated birds is meant to hold a USDA licence under the <a href="https://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/ourfocus/animalwelfare" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Animal Welfare Act, administered by USDA APHIS ↗</a>, which means an accountable identity, an inspectable facility and a real address behind the sale. We've been licensed since 2014. Ask any seller for their licence; a real one is proud to give it, and a scammer can't.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Breeder note: the paperwork we send home with every chick</h5>
        <p class={p}>Every Grey that leaves us goes home with the same folder: a PCR DNA-sexing certificate, an avian-vet health certificate, CITES Appendix I captive-bred documentation, a hatch certificate and closed band, and a written health guarantee. That folder is the difference between a companion you can prove is healthy and legal, and a bird you merely hope is. It's also, not coincidentally, exactly what a low-risk source can produce and a high-risk one can't.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>2. Rescue &amp; Adoption — Low Risk, for the Right Owner</h3>
        <p class={p}>A parrot rescue or adoption is a genuinely low-risk, ethical way to bring home an African Grey, and for an experienced owner it can be the most rewarding of all. Reputable rescues health-check their birds, are honest about history, and charge a modest adoption fee rather than a sale price. The trade-off is the bird itself: a rescue Grey often comes with a past.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>When a rescue Grey is the better choice</h4>
        <p class={p}>If you've kept parrots before and you're prepared for a bird that may be bonded to one person, nervous of hands, or a feather-plucker working through old stress, a rescue is a wonderful thing to do — you're giving a long-lived bird a second home. For a first-time owner who wants a predictable, socialised start, a hand-raised baby from a breeder is usually the gentler path. Neither is "better"; they suit different homes.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>3. Bird Expo — Mixed Risk, Verify on the Day</h3>
        <p class={p}>Bird expos and avicultural shows sit in the middle. The good news is you meet the seller and the bird in person, which beats any photo. The catch is that an expo compresses a big decision into a loud afternoon, and not every table is a licensed breeder — some are resellers. Treat an expo as a place to <em>meet</em> breeders, not to make an impulse purchase; take the card, run the same checks later, and buy when you've verified, not because the show ends at five.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>4. Pet Store — Medium Risk, High Price</h3>
        <p class={p}>A pet store is usually safer than a random online listing but pricier and shallower than a breeder. You can see the bird, and a good store health-checks its stock — but staff rarely know the bird's hatch history or socialisation, documentation is often thin, and African Greys command $3,000–$5,000 or more at retail. You're paying a premium for convenience and getting less of the paperwork and lifetime support a breeder builds in.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>5. Online Marketplace &amp; Social Sellers — the Highest Risk</h3>
        <p class={p}>Anonymous classified listings, Facebook groups and Instagram "aviaries" you can't verify are where the overwhelming majority of African Grey scams live. This is the source the forums are warning each other about. Some legitimate breeders do advertise here — but the platform gives you nothing to verify, so you must do all the checking yourself, and a seller who resists any check is telling you what you need to know.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>Why the cheapest listing is the most dangerous</h4>
        <p class={p}>On a marketplace, the lowest price is bait, not a bargain. A documented, hand-raised African Grey costs more than $1,500 to produce, so a listing well under that is almost always missing the bird, the papers, or both. The cheap number exists to switch off your caution — and once you've wired a deposit for a bird you never verified, there's usually no getting it back.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Example: the $600 "African Grey" math that never adds up</h5>
        <p class={p}>A "$600 African Grey, shipping included" cannot exist honestly: the DNA test, avian-vet exam, weeks of hand-feeding and CITES paperwork alone cost a real breeder more than that before the bird is even priced. So the $600 is paying for none of it. Either the papers don't exist, the bird was never properly raised, or — most often on marketplaces — there is no bird, just an advance-fee scam collecting "shipping deposits." The math is the tell.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: what it really costs us to raise one</h6>
        <p class={p}>Before we ever set a price, a chick has already run up months of hand-feeding, a DNA test, an avian-vet exam and its CITES paperwork. That floor is why we can't — and wouldn't — sell a documented Grey for a marketplace "bargain," and why a listing that undercuts it is undercutting the bird's own health and legality.</p>

