        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>How to Read This Table as a Buyer</h3>
        <p class={p}>Don't read down the price column and stop — that's the mistake the marketplace listing is counting on. Read <em>across</em> each row. A low price paired with "very high" scam risk and "rarely any" health record isn't a deal; it's the profile of exactly the loss you're trying to avoid. The row that stays green across all four columns is the one worth paying for.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>The column most buyers ignore (post-sale support)</h4>
        <p class={p}>There's a fifth column the table can't fully show, and it's the one seasoned owners care about most: what happens after the money's sent. A breeder answers your questions in year three when your Grey starts plucking or stops eating; a marketplace seller is unreachable by the time the box arrives. Over a 40–60 year life, that ongoing relationship is worth more than any price difference on day one — and it only exists at the top of the ranking.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-seam-logo.webp" alt="" width="160" height="53" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 9. H2-4 Identify a reputable breeder -->
        <h2 id="reputable" class={h2}>How Do You Identify a Reputable African Grey Breeder?</h2>
        <p class={p}>A reputable breeder isn't defined by a nice website — it's defined by what they'll let you check. Every genuine breeder clears the same five signals without complaint, because they have nothing to hide and everything to gain from an informed buyer. Here's what to look for, and what a risky seller does instead when you ask.</p>

        <figure class="m-0 my-6">
          <img src={igVerify.src} srcset={igVerify.srcset} sizes={igVerify.sizes} width="1200" height="655" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" alt="How to spot a reputable African Grey breeder: does a live video call, provides CITES, DNA and vet papers, shows a USDA licence, quotes one fair price, takes a reversible deposit" title="How to spot a reputable African Grey breeder | C.A.Gs" />
          <figcaption class={figc}>The five-point check a reputable breeder passes without hesitation.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <ComparisonTable columns={reputableCols} rows={reputableRows} verdict="A reputable breeder makes verification easy; a risky seller makes it awkward. If checking a seller feels like pulling teeth, that resistance is your answer." />

        <h3 class={h3}>Will They Do a Live Video Call?</h3>
        <p class={p}>This is the first and most powerful test, so lead with it. A reputable breeder will happily video-call you with the actual bird in hand — we treat it as a normal part of every sale. If a seller dodges, delays, or only ever sends photos and pre-recorded clips, stop there. Everything else on this list matters, but nothing substitutes for seeing the specific bird, alive, on demand.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Do They Provide Health Testing &amp; DNA Paperwork?</h3>
        <p class={p}>A genuine breeder tests and documents, and hands you the proof. That means a PCR DNA-sexing certificate that tells you for certain whether your Grey is male or female, and a real avian-vet examination — not a glance, but a wellness check by a qualified avian vet. If the "paperwork" is always arriving after payment, it usually never arrives at all.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>PCR DNA Sexing and the Avian-Vet Exam</h4>
        <p class={p}>Two documents do the heavy lifting here. A PCR DNA test settles your Grey's sex with certainty rather than a guess, and an avian-vet certificate records a genuine physical exam by a qualified vet. A breeder who provides both unprompted is showing you the testing a cheap seller quietly skips.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Phone the vet on the certificate before you pay</h5>
        <p class={p}>The certificate is only as good as the vet behind it, so call them. A legitimate breeder will gladly give you the clinic's number and encourage the check; a forged certificate falls apart the moment a real practice says they've never seen the bird.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Citation: the Association of Avian Veterinarians on pre-purchase exams</h6>
        <p class={p}>A pre-purchase or new-bird veterinary exam is standard best practice, and the <a href="https://www.aav.org/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Association of Avian Veterinarians ↗</a> maintains the professional standards behind it. A breeder who works with a real avian vet — and lets you phone that vet to confirm the certificate — is showing you the single clearest sign of a legitimate operation.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Can They Show CITES &amp; Captive-Bred Documentation?</h3>
        <p class={p}>Because the African Grey is CITES Appendix I, captive-bred documentation isn't optional paperwork — it's what makes owning and transporting the bird legal. A reputable breeder provides it as a matter of course; a seller who can't, or who gets vague when you ask about origin, is exposing you to a bird that may be undocumented or wild-caught.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>What the Captive-Bred Papers Actually Prove</h4>
        <p class={p}>The documentation traces your bird to a captive breeding source rather than the wild, which is what keeps ownership and interstate transport legal. It's the paper equivalent of a clean title on a car — easy to overlook until it's missing, at which point it's the only thing that matters.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Why "origin unknown" is never acceptable for an African Grey</h5>
        <p class={p}>If a seller can't say where a Grey came from, assume the worst, because on an Appendix I species "origin unknown" is a legal and ethical dead end. A reputable breeder always knows — and can show — a bird's captive-bred lineage.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: what CITES Appendix I means for you (captive-bred is legal)</h6>
        <p class={p}>African Greys were uplisted to <strong>CITES Appendix I</strong> in 2017, and the <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CITES appendices ↗</a> set the framework. That does <em>not</em> make owning one illegal — a captive-bred bird with proper documentation is entirely legal to own and transfer within the USA. It simply means the paperwork is essential, and any seller who treats it as an afterthought is a seller to avoid.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Is Their Pricing Transparent, With Real Reviews?</h3>
        <p class={p}>A reputable breeder quotes one fair, fixed figure and can point to real, verifiable reviews or references. Watch for the opposite pattern: a headline price that's suspiciously low, then "fees" for shipping, crates or paperwork that inflate it — or a wall of reviews that all sound identical and can't be traced to real buyers. Honest pricing and traceable reputation travel together.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>Reading Prices and Reviews Together</h4>
        <p class={p}>Price and reputation are best read as a pair. An honest figure backed by traceable reviews is reassuring; a bargain figure propped up by identical, unverifiable testimonials is the opposite. Treat a price that seems too good, and reviews that seem too perfect, as the same warning wearing two hats.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>What an honest price range looks like ($1,700–$3,500)</h5>
        <p class={p}>For context, a documented, hand-raised Congo runs $1,700 for a tame adult up to $2,500 for a baby, and a Timneh $1,500–$1,600 — the honest band we <a href="/blog/african-grey-parrot-price-what-you-get/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228">break down in our price guide</a>. A figure sitting comfortably in that range, quoted plainly and inclusive of the papers, is a good sign. A figure far below it is the loudest red flag there is, which is exactly where the next section starts.</p>

        <Callout variant="tip" title="Verify the breeder even when the birds look perfect">
          <p>The best-looking listings can be the most dangerous, because scammers steal real breeders' photos. Never let good photos replace the live video call and the paperwork. Run all five checks every time — a genuine breeder will thank you for it.</p>
        </Callout>

