        <!-- 11. H2-5 Red flags -->
        <h2 id="redflags" class={h2}>Red Flags That Mean Walk Away</h2>
        <p class={p}>Some warning signs are worth memorising, because they show up in almost every African Grey scam. Any single one of these is a reason to slow down; two or more together is a reason to close the tab. We won't make jokes in this section — this is the part that protects your money, and the con only works while you're excited enough to skip the obvious.</p>

        <figure class="m-0 my-6">
          <img src={igFlags.src} srcset={igFlags.srcset} sizes={igFlags.sizes} width="1200" height="655" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" alt="African Grey buyer red flags to walk away from: too-low price, no CITES DNA or vet paperwork, no live video call, wire gift-card or crypto payment, and high-pressure urgency" title="African Grey red flags: walk away | C.A.Gs" />
          <figcaption class={figc}>The red flags that mean walk away — before you pay anyone.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <ComparisonTable columns={["Red flag", "What it usually means"]} rows={flagRows} verdict="Any one of these is a reason to pause. Two or more is a scam in progress — keep your money and move on." />

        <h3 class={h3}>The Five Warning Signs, in Detail</h3>
        <p class={p}>Each of these deserves a closer look, because scammers rely on you recognising none of them until the money's gone. Read them once now and they'll jump out at you the next time a listing feels too good to be true.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>Price Far Below Market</h4>
        <p class={p}>A price well under the $1,700 floor is the most common bait in the trade. A legitimate, documented, hand-raised African Grey simply costs more than that to produce, so a bargain listing isn't generosity — it's the hook. The gap between the "deal" and the real price is precisely the testing, papers and weaning that were skipped, or the bird that was never there.</p>

        <h4 class={h4}>No Paperwork or Vet Records</h4>
        <p class={p}>If a seller can't produce CITES documentation, a DNA certificate and an avian-vet record before you pay, treat the bird as undocumented — because that's what it is. "Papers coming later" is the single most reliable phrase in a bird scam. Real documentation exists before the sale; a promise of documentation after payment is a promise scammers make and never keep.</p>

        <h4 class={h4}>Crypto, Gift-Card or Wire-Only Payment</h4>
        <p class={p}>The payment method is often the clearest tell of all. Scammers insist on wire transfers, gift cards or cryptocurrency for one reason: those payments are irreversible, so once you've sent the money it's gone. A legitimate breeder takes a payment you can dispute and reverse. Anyone who <em>only</em> accepts irreversible methods is choosing the one option that leaves you no recourse.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Reversible payment is your only real safety net</h5>
        <p class={p}>A payment you can dispute is the difference between a bad experience and an unrecoverable loss. Insist on one, and a scammer's favourite tools — wire, gift cards, crypto — lose their power entirely.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Citation: the FTC on reversible vs irreversible payments</h6>
        <p class={p}>Consumer-protection guidance is blunt on this point. As <a href="https://consumer.ftc.gov/consumer-alerts/2024/12/getting-pet-avoid-scams" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the FTC's advice on avoiding pet scams ↗</a> spells out, demands for wire transfers, gift cards or crypto are a defining signature of pet-purchase fraud, and the <a href="https://www.bbb.org/scamtracker" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Better Business Bureau's scam tracker ↗</a> logs these advance-fee pet cons by the thousand. Use a reversible method, every time.</p>

        <h4 class={h4}>Urgency &amp; Pressure Tactics</h4>
        <p class={p}>"Another buyer is deciding tonight." "I need the deposit in the next hour to hold her." Manufactured urgency exists to stop you running the checks in this guide. A real breeder understands that a 40–60 year commitment deserves a few days' thought and will hold a reasonable, reversible deposit without drama. If someone is rushing you, they're rushing you past the very step that would expose them.</p>

        <MythFact
          myth="If the seller has lots of photos and a professional-looking website, the bird must be real and it's safe to pay."
          fact="Photos and slick sites are the easiest things to fake — scammers routinely steal real breeders' images. Legitimacy is proven by a live video call, verifiable paperwork and a reversible payment, not by how polished the listing looks. Verify the seller, not the screenshots." />

