        <!-- 12. H2-6 Why C.A.Gs -->
        <h2 id="why" class={h2}>Why Buyers Choose C.A.Gs (and How We Rank Ourselves Honestly)</h2>
        <p class={p}>We put ourselves at the top of the ranking, so it's only fair we show our work. Here at C.A.Gs, we're not the cheapest listing you'll find and we'd never pretend to be — we're the source that passes every check in this guide, because we built the aviary around exactly those checks. Most of our buyers reach us after a scare somewhere else, wanting a bird they can verify, and here's what that looks like.</p>

        <figure class="m-0 my-6">
          <img src={igTrust.src} srcset={igTrust.srcset} sizes={igTrust.sizes} width="1200" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" alt="Mark and Teri Benjamin with a hand-raised Congo African Grey at C.A.Gs in Midland, Texas — a verifiable, USDA-licensed breeder" title="Why buyers choose C.A.Gs | C.A.Gs" />
          <figcaption class={figc}>A verifiable, USDA-licensed breeder — real people, real birds, real paperwork.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Health Testing &amp; a Written Guarantee</h3>
        <p class={p}>Every C.A.Gs Grey is PCR DNA-sexed, examined by an avian vet, and screened for the diseases that matter, then sent home with a written health guarantee and the certificates to match. You're not hoping the bird is healthy; you're holding the paperwork that proves it — and you're welcome to call the vet on the certificate to confirm every word before you commit.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Hand-Raising &amp; Socialisation</h3>
        <p class={p}>Our birds are hand-raised in our home in Midland, Texas — fed, handled and gentled every day from hatching — so they arrive bonded to people and ready to learn. That daily work is the whole reason a well-raised Grey is calm on your hand and quick to <a href="/blog/african-grey-parrot-training/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228">start training and talking</a>, and it's the one thing a marketplace flipper can't fake with a stolen photo.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Lifetime Breeder Support + Nationwide Shipping</h3>
        <p class={p}>When you buy from us, the relationship doesn't end at the airport. We answer questions for the life of the bird — the plucking scare in year three, the diet question in year eight — and we ship nationwide on IATA-compliant flights, $185 to your nearest airport or $350 home delivery. That combination of verifiable documentation and a breeder who stays reachable is exactly what the top of the ranking is supposed to mean.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>What "Lifetime Support" Means in Practice</h4>
        <p class={p}>It means you have a number to call for the next four decades, not just until the sale clears. New Grey owners hit the same milestones — the first moult, the first tantrum, the first vet scare — and having the breeder who raised the bird on the other end of the line is worth more than any discount.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Shipping that's safe, tracked and IATA-compliant</h5>
        <p class={p}>Distance rarely needs to decide this purchase. Our birds travel on IATA-compliant Delta, United or American flights — $185 to your nearest airport or $350 home — crated, monitored and documented the whole way, so a verifiable breeder a few states away is still the safer choice.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: the buyers who came to us after nearly losing a deposit</h6>
        <p class={p}>We hear the same story constantly: a "$700 African Grey" on a marketplace, a seller pushing gift cards, a knot in the stomach — and a search that finally led somewhere they could verify. It's why this whole page exists. We'd genuinely rather you ran every check in this guide on <em>us</em> and bought with total confidence than sent a hopeful deposit to someone who couldn't pass a single one.</p>

        <BreederNote>
          <p>If you remember one line from this page, make it this: you're not choosing a bird, you're choosing a source you can verify. Run the live-video and paperwork checks on every seller — including us — and buy from whoever passes without flinching. The right African Grey from the right source is a 40–60 year joy; the wrong one from the wrong source is a heartbreak you can avoid with five minutes of questions.</p>
        </BreederNote>

